{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_016e2wsxuXMcNGKy5Cvj1MFT","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the framework provided.\n\n**Behavior 1**: The content passed to the summary-generation step includes data retrieved from all three sources.\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about whether data from all three sources is correctly passed/combined and forwarded to the summary step. This is a module boundary issue — the data collection layer needs to aggregate from three sources and pass it to the summary step. This is a handoff between modules.\n- REAL-INFRA: The three sources are a metrics endpoint, issue tracker API, and deployment log. But the question is whether the failure mode requires real infrastructure. The failure here is about whether the orchestration code correctly collects from all three sources and passes all data to the summary step. \n- MOCK-HIDE: An in-process mock of the three data sources could catch if the orchestration logic forgets to include one source's data, so mocking won't hide this failure — the test would still catch whether all three are being aggregated and passed through.\n- LLM-DEP: No — this is about what content is passed to the summary step, not about the quality of the summary.\n- MULTI-STEP: No single step.\n\nEVIDENCE-LEVEL: This is an integration test — the failure mode is whether multiple modules are properly wired together to feed the summary step.\n\nOUTPUT-LEVEL: Integration\n\nINTEGRATION-BRAKE: I can use mocked HTTP clients and fake deployment logs without needing real OS/network or AI/ML components, and there's no multi-step agentic behavior involved.\n\nFor the second behavior, I'm looking at error handling when a data source becomes unavailable — the orchestration layer needs to catch that error and continue producing a report with a note about the missing section rather than failing entirely. This is a module boundary interaction where the collector encounters an error and the orchestration layer must handle it gracefully. I can simulate the unavailability with a stub that raises a connection error.\n\nFor the third behavior, I'm checking whether the narrative summary accurately captures the key values from the input data — this depends on the LLM's generation quality.  A mock would just return whatever I programmed it to, so it wouldn't catch real failures. Since the behavior specifically asks about accuracy of the actual summary, this requires a real LLM and lands at the Agentic level. The fourth behavior is about the complete end-to-end pipeline working correctly, from data collection through email delivery to the recipient's inbox.\n\nFor this one, the email delivery part definitely needs real infrastructure or at least a test email service to verify actual inbox receipt. The pipeline chains together data collection from APIs, LLM-based narrative generation, and email delivery — multiple steps in sequence. The data sources themselves are deterministic APIs rather than LLM-based, so the agentic complexity really comes from the narrative generation and delivery steps working together. The summary generation is LLM-based, followed by email delivery. Since the pipeline chains data collection through LLM generation to email delivery with real infrastructure verification (checking that emails actually reach the inbox), this qualifies as a full agent pipeline at the Workflow level.\n\nFor the fallback behavior when email delivery fails, the system saves the generated report instead. to a local file and delivery is retried on the next scheduled run.\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This involves error handling when email fails AND retry on next scheduled run. The \"retry on next scheduled run\" implies state persistence (saving to local file) and then re-reading on next run.\n- REAL-INFRA: The email unreachability can be simulated. The local file save/read can be tested with real filesystem or temp directory. \"Next scheduled run\" implies simulating two runs.\n- LLM-DEP: The report is already generated (or could be pre-generated for this test). The behavior is about the error handling and retry mechanism, not about generation quality.\n- MOCK-HIDE: Could we mock the filesystem? The behavior involves actual file I/O — writing and reading from local file. If we mock the filesystem, we might miss real file handling issues. But the actual failure mode is about the retry logic and file persistence mechanism.\n\nSo the core test is really about control flow and state persistence across invocations. I can mock the email client to fail, use a real temp directory for file operations, and just call the pipeline function twice sequentially to simulate the scheduled runs without needing actual scheduling infrastructure. The key question is whether \"next scheduled run\" means the retry is baked into the scheduling infrastructure itself, or if it's just checking for pending reports on startup—and since the behavior can be tested by calling the function twice in sequence, I can keep this at Integration level rather than escalating to System testing.\n\nNow I'm settling on the final confidence levels and preparing the structured summary.\n\nFor the first behavior, Integration is the sweet spot since it tests the real aggregation logic across module boundaries with mocked data sources. For the second, Integration again captures the orchestration continuing after an error without needing full system infrastructure. The third behavior is different—it genuinely needs a real LLM to verify accuracy, so Agentic testing is the right call, since mocking would just hide failures.\n\nNow looking at the remaining behaviors: the fourth one requires the full pipeline including the LLM step and actual email verification, making Workflow testing essential at 65% confidence. The fifth behavior focuses on error handling, file persistence, and retry logic without LLM involvement, so Integration testing at 60% is the appropriate level.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":10103,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":10103},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d48402e9-0524-44ed-b254-180f873488db","uuid":"d0ac18cc-b06b-445e-b6c3-778b59f081c0"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_016e2wsxuXMcNGKy5Cvj1MFT","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_012TxhPHoSeEmcqpBEqkeitX","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Content passed to summary-generation includes data from all three sources.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is whether the orchestration layer correctly gathers outputs from all three collectors and hands all of them to the summary step — a module-boundary handoff failure, not a single-function logic bug. REAL-INFRA: The three sources (metrics endpoint, issue tracker API, deployment log) can each be replaced by in-process stubs/mock HTTP clients; no real network or OS primitives are needed to catch an orchestrator that silently drops one source's payload. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking the sources is fine here because the behavior under test is the aggregation/forwarding logic, not source response quality. LLM-DEP: This behavior checks what is *passed to* the generation step, not what the LLM produces — no AI/ML output quality involved. MULTI-STEP: Single orchestration step. INTEGRATION-BRAKE: (a) No real OS/network needed; (b) no AI/ML dependency; (c) no chained agentic steps. COMMIT-TO-REASONING: Evidence points to Integration; output is Integration — no override.","test_description":"Wire the orchestrator with three stub data-source clients (one for each of metrics, issue tracker, and deployment log), each returning distinct sentinel payloads. Invoke the pipeline up to but not including summary generation (or capture what is passed to the summary step). Assert that the payload forwarded to summary generation contains data from all three stubs and that none is missing or zero-valued.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.15,"Agentic":0.06,"Workflow":0.04}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When one data source is unavailable, the report is produced with a 'data unavailable' note rather than aborting.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure appears when the orchestration layer catches an error from one collector and decides whether to continue or abort — this is a control-flow decision at a module boundary, not a pure single-function logic test. REAL-INFRA: Source unavailability can be faithfully simulated by a stub that raises a connection exception or returns a 5xx; no real network is required to expose the abort-vs-continue branching bug. MOCK-HIDE: A mock that raises an exception is exactly the right probe here — it is not hiding anything because the failure mode is the orchestrator's response to the exception, not the source's actual network behavior. LLM-DEP: No AI/ML output involved. MULTI-STEP: Single error-handling path. INTEGRATION-BRAKE: (a) No real OS/network needed; (b) no AI/ML dependency; (c) no chained agentic steps. COMMIT-TO-REASONING: Evidence points to Integration; output is Integration — no override.","test_description":"Configure the orchestrator with two healthy stub sources and one stub that raises a connection error. Run the full data-collection phase. Assert that the pipeline does not raise an exception, that the output data structure contains 'data unavailable' (or equivalent sentinel) for the failing source's section, and that the other two sections contain valid data.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.18,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.13,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The narrative summary accurately represents the key values present in the input data.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: 'Accurately represents' is a quality/faithfulness judgment about LLM-generated prose. A stub or mock LLM would return whatever string we hard-code, making the test trivially pass regardless of whether the real model hallucinates, inverts, or drops key values — the entire failure mode is hidden. Running the test 100 times with a real model may yield different outputs; the correctness criterion is non-deterministic and model-dependent. MOCK-MISS / MOCK-HIDE: Any deterministic replacement for the LLM hides the exact class of failure the behavior describes. REAL-INFRA: No real OS/network primitives required beyond the LLM API call. MULTI-STEP: Single generation step. REJECTION-GATE: Demoting to Integration would require behavior text indicating that a stub LLM suffices to verify narrative accuracy — no such text exists. COMMIT-TO-REASONING: Evidence points unambiguously to Agentic; output is Agentic — no override.","test_description":"Feed a known, structured input payload (with specific numeric metrics, issue counts, and deployment records containing distinctive values) to the real summary-generation step using the real LLM. Assert that the produced narrative contains or correctly states the distinctive key values (e.g., specific metric figures, counts), and does not contradict them. Run with a fixed seed or multiple samples to account for non-determinism.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.73,"Workflow":0.12}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A complete report — from data collection through email delivery — reaches the configured recipient's inbox correctly.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"MULTI-STEP: The pipeline chains: (1) data collection from three external sources, (2) LLM-based narrative generation (agentic step), and (3) email delivery to a real inbox. Even if data collection uses stubs, the LLM generation is a real agentic step and verifying the email was 'received correctly' in an inbox requires real email infrastructure. A pipeline that includes at least one agentic step and traverses real external delivery infrastructure constitutes a full agent pipeline per the Workflow definition. LLM-DEP: The summary content in the delivered email depends on real LLM output — a mock would hide generation failures that cause garbled or empty emails. REAL-INFRA: 'Reaches the configured recipient's inbox correctly' cannot be verified with a stub SMTP client — the failure mode (email not received, garbled, wrong recipient) only surfaces with real delivery infrastructure. REJECTION-GATE: Demoting to Agentic would require the behavior to say 'verify the generated content' without end-to-end delivery verification; the text explicitly includes inbox receipt. COMMIT-TO-REASONING: Evidence points to Workflow; output is Workflow — no override.","test_description":"Run the full pipeline end-to-end against stub data sources (returning representative payloads), a real LLM for summary generation, and a real (or sandbox) email service. Assert that a message arrives in the recipient's test inbox, that it contains a non-empty subject and body, and that the body references values present in the stub data. Use a test inbox (e.g., Mailhog or a designated test account) rather than a production address.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.18,"Workflow":0.67}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When email delivery is unreachable, the report is saved to a local file and delivery is retried on the next scheduled run.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure spans module boundaries: the email client raises an error → the error handler writes the report to a local file → on a subsequent invocation the pipeline reads the saved file and reattempts delivery. Each handoff is a potential failure point not catchable by a single-function unit test. REAL-INFRA: Email unreachability can be simulated with a stub that raises a connection error. File I/O uses the local filesystem (a real temp directory is appropriate) but no real OS-level primitives beyond standard file operations are needed. 'Next scheduled run' can be reproduced by invoking the pipeline entry point twice in the same test process — no real cron or scheduler infrastructure required. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking the filesystem would hide real file-write/read failures, but using a real temp directory avoids this. LLM-DEP: The report is already generated before this behavior's failure mode activates; no AI/ML output quality is at issue. MULTI-STEP: The two sequential pipeline invocations are deterministic, not agentic. INTEGRATION-BRAKE: (a) No real network/OS primitives beyond local filesystem; (b) no AI/ML dependency; (c) no chained agentic steps. COMMIT-TO-REASONING: Evidence points to Integration; output is Integration — no override.","test_description":"Set up the pipeline with a real temp directory and a stub email client configured to fail on the first call and succeed on the second. Invoke the pipeline once (first 'scheduled run'): assert no exception is raised, the email was not sent, and a report file exists in the temp directory. Invoke the pipeline a second time (next 'scheduled run'): assert the email stub was called, the report content matches what was saved, and the local file is cleaned up (or marked delivered) after successful retry.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.12,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.18,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.03}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":10103,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":10103},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d48402e9-0524-44ed-b254-180f873488db","uuid":"12638c3e-f028-4896-9bd6-41b342708cb8"}
